Among the many suggestions promoted by the government to promote long marriages, one was the creation of a Tax on Divorce; Taxation is, after all, the power forbear by which governments often measure the value of their exploits. Taxes of love do not inspire many citizens to remain in wedlock.

Divorce in Greece does have a legal element, however. The dissolution of a marriage in Greece is by law a civil process and must be brought to the attention of the Court where the parties reside. If the spouses do not reside in the same city, the Court in the place where the property of the marriage was registered presides over the divorce. Divorce does not have to wait until three years of separation has elapsed. Separation does not terminate a legal marriage and only dissolution of the marriage can.

The grounds upon which divorce is granted in Greece are many and varied. Divorce may be granted on the basis of irreconcilable differences (insănatosirea in Greaca). The Law provides information of irreconcilable differences and these can be viewed in the Ministry of Justice Laws in Greek. Actions for divorce can also be brought on the grounds of living apart, residence and nationality. The Law details many other grounds for divorce including what are the consequences of misrepresenting facts, domestic violence, adultery, mental and physical cruelty, abandonment of the spouses, poisoning an individual, institutionalising or restricting the freedom of a spouse.
